\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The manifesto states that the public largely accepts individual technological advancements as purely positive without accounting for their overall effect, which includes the erosion of local and individual freedom and autonomy. While originally regarded as a thoughtful critique of modern society, with roots in the work of academic authors such as\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Ellul"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Jacques Ellul}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desmond_Morris"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Desmond Morris}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , and\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Seligman"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Martin Seligman}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrial_Society_and_Its_Future#cite_note-3"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 3]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Kaczynski's 1996 trial polarized public opinion around the essay, as his court-appointed lawyers tried to justify their insanity defense around characterizing the manifesto as the work of a madman, and the prosecution lawyers rested their case on it being produced by a lucid mind.}{ }
